1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,340
The Florida Everglades stretch across
millions of acres of slow-moving water and dense sawgrass

2
00:00:07,340 --> 00:00:10,960
It is one of the most specialized ecosystems
on Earth

3
00:00:10,960 --> 00:00:16,200
but right now, a massive predator is moving
just beneath the surface

4
00:00:16,200 --> 00:00:18,760
and it was never supposed to be here

5
00:00:18,760 --> 00:00:26,220
In the 1980s, Miami established itself as
the exotic pet capital of the United States

6
00:00:26,220 --> 00:00:32,360
importing thousands of foreign reptiles
through its ports every single year

7
00:00:32,360 --> 00:00:40,660
Consumers purchased baby Burmese pythons
with no understanding of their explosive growth rate

8
00:00:40,660 --> 00:00:46,440
Within months, these snakes reached lengths
that made them impossible to keep

9
00:00:46,440 --> 00:00:49,200
When the pythons outgrew their enclosures

10
00:00:49,200 --> 00:00:54,920
overwhelmed owners drove to the nearest
swamp and dumped them illegally into the wild

11
00:00:54,920 --> 00:00:58,840
seeding the wetlands with an apex predator

12
00:00:58,840 --> 00:01:05,960
Then in August of 1992, Hurricane Andrew — a
Category 5 storm

13
00:01:05,960 --> 00:01:11,460
tore through South Florida and destroyed a
commercial python breeding facility

14
00:01:11,460 --> 00:01:17,640
releasing hundreds of snakes into the
Everglades in a single catastrophic night

15
00:01:17,640 --> 00:01:25,080
For years, researchers dismissed sightings
as isolated incidents. But by the year 2000

16
00:01:25,080 --> 00:01:28,120
scientists confirmed what they feared

17
00:01:28,120 --> 00:01:33,720
the pythons had become a fully established,
self-reproducing population in the wild

18
00:01:33,720 --> 00:01:37,700
These snakes have no natural predators in
Florida

19
00:01:37,700 --> 00:01:41,840
A single female can lay up to 100 eggs per
clutch

20
00:01:41,840 --> 00:01:45,200
Their camouflage makes them nearly invisible

21
00:01:45,200 --> 00:01:51,560
And they have systematically consumed the
Everglades' native mammals into near extinction

22
00:01:51,560 --> 00:01:57,040
Raccoon and opossum populations have
collapsed by 99 percent

23
00:01:57,040 --> 00:02:04,440
Marsh rabbits and foxes are now considered
locally extinct across most python-invaded areas

24
00:02:04,440 --> 00:02:08,320
The food web is being dismantled from the
bottom up

25
00:02:08,320 --> 00:02:11,520
But the pythons didn't stop at small mammals

26
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:13,640
They moved up the food chain

27
00:02:13,640 --> 00:02:18,760
successfully hunting and consuming the
region's own apex predator

28
00:02:18,760 --> 00:02:23,000
the American alligator. Predator eating
predator

29
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:27,480
In response, scientists launched the scout
snake program

30
00:02:27,480 --> 00:02:33,400
They capture male pythons, surgically
implant radio transmitters beneath their scales

31
00:02:33,400 --> 00:02:36,200
and release them back into the wild

32
00:02:36,200 --> 00:02:42,360
These tracked males then lead biologists
directly to hidden breeding aggregations

33
00:02:42,360 --> 00:02:49,400
clusters of females that would otherwise
remain completely undetectable in the dense swamp

34
00:02:49,400 --> 00:02:54,040
At night, wildlife officers wade into
pitch-black swamp water

35
00:02:54,040 --> 00:02:57,560
armed with nothing but headlamps and snake
hooks

36
00:02:57,560 --> 00:02:58,840
Their mission

37
00:02:58,840 --> 00:03:03,400
capture these massive pythons by hand, one
at a time

38
00:03:03,400 --> 00:03:10,920
A single 16-foot python generates enough
muscular force to overpower three grown men

39
00:03:10,920 --> 00:03:14,200
Every capture is a violent, physical
struggle

40
00:03:14,200 --> 00:03:18,600
against hundreds of pounds of raw
constricting power

41
00:03:18,600 --> 00:03:22,760
Florida has also mobilized civilian forces

42
00:03:22,760 --> 00:03:27,320
Every year, nearly a thousand hunters travel
from across the globe

43
00:03:27,320 --> 00:03:30,520
to compete in the Florida Python Challenge

44
00:03:30,520 --> 00:03:36,520
a 10-day event with $ 10, 000 in prize money
on the line

45
00:03:36,520 --> 00:03:40,360
Between civilian events and state-funded
contractors

46
00:03:40,360 --> 00:03:45,960
more than 23, 000 pythons have been removed
from Florida's public lands

47
00:03:45,960 --> 00:03:48,760
But statistical models suggest that number

48
00:03:48,760 --> 00:03:53,400
represents less than one percent of the
actual population

49
00:03:53,400 --> 00:03:55,720
The state has pivoted to technology

50
00:03:55,720 --> 00:04:01,320
Engineering teams have mounted 850-nanometer
near-infrared cameras

51
00:04:01,320 --> 00:04:05,080
to patrol vehicles, scanning for python heat
signatures

52
00:04:05,080 --> 00:04:08,680
that are completely invisible to the naked
eye

53
00:04:08,680 --> 00:04:11,640
Biologists are testing the water itself

54
00:04:11,640 --> 00:04:16,520
analyzing environmental DNA to confirm a
python's recent presence

55
00:04:16,520 --> 00:04:21,480
in a specific area, even weeks after the
snake has moved on

56
00:04:21,480 --> 00:04:24,200
The invisible made detectable

57
00:04:24,200 --> 00:04:28,440
But now, genetic testing has revealed a new
complication

58
00:04:28,440 --> 00:04:33,240
The Burmese pythons are actively hybridizing
with the Indian rock python

59
00:04:33,240 --> 00:04:38,280
a smaller, faster species — creating
offspring with increased genetic vigor

60
00:04:38,280 --> 00:04:40,200
and adaptability

61
00:04:40,200 --> 00:04:47,480
2025 range data shows these hybrids pushing
beyond South Florida's borders

62
00:04:47,480 --> 00:04:51,720
advancing steadily into new counties to the
north

63
00:04:51,720 --> 00:04:55,080
With a warming climate removing cold
barriers

64
00:04:55,080 --> 00:04:58,360
their expansion may be unstoppable

65
00:04:58,360 --> 00:05:04,040
Total eradication is no longer considered a
realistic scientific goal

66
00:05:04,040 --> 00:05:08,440
The state has shifted its entire strategy to
permanent damage control

67
00:05:08,440 --> 00:05:13,320
and the protection of whatever native
habitats still remain

68
00:05:13,320 --> 00:05:16,520
The Burmese python has proven how a single

69
00:05:16,520 --> 00:05:19,720
unchecked invasive species can permanently

70
00:05:19,720 --> 00:05:24,040
and irreversibly alter a fragile ecosystem

71
00:05:24,040 --> 00:05:26,440
Florida is holding the line

72
00:05:26,440 --> 00:05:30,120
but it remains to be seen if the Everglades
can endure

73
00:05:30,120 --> 00:05:34,360
or if this landscape has already been
surrendered to the python
